# CODEOWNERS for Enterprise Governance
#
# This file enforces that the Platform Team must approve changes to
# critical files across all repositories.
#
# GitHub Enterprise Feature: CODEOWNERS
# Purpose: Prevent developers from modifying security-critical files without review
# Limitation: Manual review doesn't scale to 1000 repos, subtle bypasses slip through
#
# See: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners

# ==============================================================================
# WORKFLOW FILES - Platform Team MUST approve
# ==============================================================================
# Any changes to CI/CD workflows require Platform Engineering approval
# This prevents developers from:
# - Removing security scanning jobs
# - Changing approval gates
# - Modifying deployment logic
#
# BUT: At 1000 repos, platform team can't catch subtle bypasses like:
# - continue-on-error: true
# - exit-code: 0 instead of 1
# - Conditional skips (if: contains(..., 'skip'))

/.github/workflows/ @platform-team @security-team

# ==============================================================================
# SECURITY POLICIES - Security Team MUST approve
# ==============================================================================
# Changes to security policies require Security Team approval
# This includes OPA/Rego policies, security scanning configuration

/platform/policies/ @security-team @platform-team

# ==============================================================================
# DEPLOYMENT MANIFESTS - Platform Team MUST approve
# ==============================================================================
# Kubernetes manifests, Dockerfiles, and deployment configs
# This prevents developers from:
# - Running as root
# - Disabling security contexts
# - Opening privileged ports

**/Dockerfile @platform-team @security-team
**/k8s/ @platform-team
**/manifests/ @platform-team
/gitops/ @platform-team

# ==============================================================================
# INFRASTRUCTURE CODE - Platform Team MUST approve
# ==============================================================================
# Terraform, CloudFormation, infrastructure-as-code

/infrastructure/ @platform-team
*.tf @platform-team
*.tfvars @platform-team

# ==============================================================================
# CODEOWNERS FILE ITSELF - Platform Team + Security Team
# ==============================================================================
# Prevent developers from modifying who reviews what

/.github/CODEOWNERS @platform-team @security-team

# ==============================================================================
# LIMITATIONS AT SCALE (1000 repos)
# ==============================================================================
#
# What CODEOWNERS provides:
# ✅ Requires designated team approval for specific files
# ✅ Blocks PR merge without approval
# ✅ Clear ownership model
#
# What CODEOWNERS DOESN'T prevent:
# ❌ Subtle bypasses in workflow files:
#    - continue-on-error: true (looks like error handling)
#    - exit-code: 0 (looks like a config change)
#    - if: "!contains(...)" (conditional logic)
# ❌ Scale issues:
#    - Platform team must review changes across ALL 1000 repos
#    - 10-20 PRs/day × 1000 repos = unsustainable
#    - Context switching between different services
# ❌ Timing issues:
#    - Review happens pre-merge, not pre-deploy
#    - Developer can still merge after approval, then deploy immediately
#
# Example bypass that passes code review:
#
# jobs:
#   security-scan:
#     runs-on: ubuntu-latest
#     continue-on-error: true  # ← Reviewer might think this is for stability
#     steps:
#       - uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@master
#         with:
#           exit-code: 0  # ← Reviewer might miss this change
#
# Platform reviewer approves (looks reasonable)
# ❌ But security scanning now NEVER fails
#
# ==============================================================================
# COMPARE TO HARNESS
# ==============================================================================
#
# In Harness:
# - Templates live OUTSIDE developer repos
# - Developers reference templates, cannot modify
# - No code review needed (developers can't edit)
# - Locked stages = architecturally impossible to bypass
# - Scales to unlimited repos
#
# Configuration:
# ```yaml
# template:
#   stages:
#     - stage:
#         name: Security
#         locked: true  # ← Developers CANNOT modify
# ```
#
# No CODEOWNERS needed because developers don't control templates.
#
